Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: Agricultural markets are inherently complex systems influenced by both temporal dynamics (e.g., seasonal cycles, trends) and spatial interactions (e.g., regional supply chains, climatic spillovers). While prior work in spatio-temporal modeling has advanced through graph neural networks and temporal convolutions, most approaches assume static spatial relationships or rely on predefined geographic proximity. However, in agricultural pricing and volume data, the underlying spatial dependencies are not fixed—they evolve due to changing market conditions, policy interventions, transportation disruptions, or climate shocks. Inspired by Paper 1’s dynamic graph learning framework and Paper 2’s decomposition of static and dynamic spatial relations, I propose a novel architecture that *learns* evolving spatial graphs from data while jointly modeling price and volume as interdependent time series. Unlike existing methods that treat space as fixed or use heuristic adjacency matrices, our approach dynamically infers latent trade and influence networks at each time step. Furthermore, drawing from the continuous-time insights in Paper 3, we incorporate causal regularization to ensure that predictions respect economic plausibility—such as Granger-style causality between volume shocks and price adjustments—thereby improving generalization and interpretability. This integration of dual temporal convolutional networks with dynamic graph learning and causal constraints is novel in the agricultural economics and ML4Science domains, offering both predictive accuracy and mechanistic insight into market dynamics.

